06673nam a22007215i 9780889207516DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20061983xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892075167 a10.51644/97808892075162doi  a(DE-B1597)667857  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBM42b.T78 1983eb 7aREL0400002bisacsh04a29600aTruth and Compassion :bEssays on Judaism and Religion in Memory of Rabbi Dr Solomon Frank /ced. by Jack N. Lightstone, Howard Joseph, Michael Oppenheim. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©1983  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSR Supplements ;v1200tFront Matter -- tContents -- tDedicatory Preface -- tIntroduction -- tA Comparative Study of Charity in Christianity and Judaism -- tJudaism of the Second Commonwealth: Toward a Reform of the Scholarly Tradition -- tJacob al-Kirkisani on the Reality of Magic and the Nature of the Miraculous: A Study in Tenth-Century Karaite Rationalism -- tA Key to Nineteenth-Century Critical Attitudes Toward Religion? The Work of Jean Jacques Rousseau -- tWalter Benjamin, the Mystical Materialist -- tSome Underlying Issues of Modern Jewish Philosophy -- tReflections on the "Whig" Interpretation of Jewish History; Ma'assei banim siman le-'avot -- tBetween Dignity and Redemption: A Critique of Soloveitchik's Adam I and Adam II -- tOur Torah, Your Torah, and Their Torah: An Evaluation of the Artscroll Phenomenon -- tSome Jewish Theological Reflections on the Holocaust* -- tBack Matter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThese essays represent a multidisciplinary approach to the study of religion and, especially, Judaism. Setting aside common scholarly concerns with source criticism and history of interpretation, Shimon Levy argues that in Numbers 11 the redactor has forged diverse elements into a unity. Observing that much of what is said about Second Commonwealth Judaic culture is speculative, Jack Lightstone calls for radical revision of accepted portrayals of the period. Ira Robinson's study of al-Kirkisani's effort to differentiate magic and miracle while demonstrating the rationality of belief in miracle locates his thoughts in the context of Rabbinic and Muslim treatments of the subject. While historians of modern Judaism have acknowledged in the influence of Kant and Hegel, Rousseau, contends Michel Despland, is often overlooked; he opened the way for changes in social and religious life. In Walter Benjamin's philosophy of history Charles Davis finds a significant combining of elements from Kabbalistic and Marxist thought. Michael Oppenheim finds a common core of concerns addressed by modern Jewish philosophers: a struggle with modernity, identification with Jewish thought and values, and commitment to their Jewish communities. Gershon Hundert's "Reflections on the 'Whig' Interpretation of Jewish History" argues—vis-à-vis the Jerusalem school of Zionist historians—that the responsibility of national historians to their community can be fulfilled only by repudiating ideologies that may stand in the way of the search for truth. Howard Joseph's survey of teh extensive literature on the Holocaust indicates the options the authors find most worthy of continued focus. Jerome Eckstein critically examines one of the few published pieces by Joseph Soloveitchik, who combines the Talmudic genius of the Lithuanian Yeshiva world with mastery of the Western intellectual tradition. B. Barry Levy's study of the Artscroll series of translations of and commentaries on biblical literature examines the assumptions and methodology of the series and the hidden agenda that emerges. Frederick Bird's comparison of charity ethics in Judaism and Christianity draws attention to the imprint on these ethics of the formative period of each religion. The volume will be of interest to student of the Bible, Judaism, and Christianity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHebrew languagevTexts. 0aJudaismxHistory. 0aJudaism. 0aJudaïsme. 0aReligion. 4aHistory: Jewish Studies. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / General.2bisacsh1 aBird, Frederick B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDespland, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEckstein, Jerome, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHundert, Gershon David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoseph, Howard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLevy, B. Barry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLightstone, Jack N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLightstone, Jack N., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOppenheim, Michael D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOppenheim, Michael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRobinson, Ira, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920751640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889207516423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889207516/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles